Ensemble Techniques Project - Travel Package Purchase Prediction¶

Context

Tourism company called "Visit with us" wants to enable and establish a viable business model to expand the customer base. Currently, there are 5 types of packages the company is offering - Basic, Standard, Deluxe, Super Deluxe, King. To expland more, they would like to introduce a new product package called - Wellness Tourism Package. Company wants to target the customer base who can potentially buy their newly introduced package.

Objective

Using ensemble techniques like Bagging and Boosing analyze the customers' data to predict which customer is more likely to purchase the newly introduced travel package.

Data Dictionary

Customer details:

CustomerID: Unique customer ID

ProdTaken: Whether the customer has purchased a package or not (0: No, 1: Yes)

Age: Age of customer

TypeofContact: How customer was contacted (Company Invited or Self Inquiry)

CityTier: City tier depends on the development of a city, population, facilities, and living standards. The categories are ordered i.e. Tier 1 > Tier 2 > Tier 3. It's the city the customer lives in.

Occupation: Occupation of customer

Gender: Gender of customer

NumberOfPersonVisiting: Total number of persons planning to take the trip with the customer

PreferredPropertyStar: Preferred hotel property rating by customer

MaritalStatus: Marital status of customer

NumberOfTrips: Average number of trips in a year by customer

Passport: The customer has a passport or not (0: No, 1: Yes)

OwnCar: Whether the customers own a car or not (0: No, 1: Yes)

NumberOfChildrenVisiting: Total number of children with age less than 5 planning to take the trip with the customer

Designation: Designation of the customer in the current organization

MonthlyIncome: Gross monthly income of the customer

Customer interaction data

PitchSatisfactionScore: Sales pitch satisfaction score

ProductPitched: Product pitched by the salesperson

NumberOfFollowups: Total number of follow-ups has been done by the salesperson after the sales pitch

DurationOfPitch: Duration of the pitch by a salesperson to the customer

def histogram_boxplot(data, feature, figsize=(12, 7), kde=False, bins=None):
    """
    Boxplot and histogram combined

    data: dataframe
    feature: dataframe column
    figsize: size of figure (default (12,7))
    kde: whether to show the density curve (default False)
    bins: number of bins for histogram (default None)
    """
    f2, (ax_box2, ax_hist2) = plt.subplots(
        nrows=2,  # Number of rows of the subplot grid= 2
        sharex=True,  # x-axis will be shared among all subplots
        gridspec_kw={"height_ratios": (0.25, 0.75)},
        figsize=figsize)  # creating the 2 subplots
    
    sns.boxplot(data=data, x=feature, ax=ax_box2, showmeans=True, color="violet")  # boxplot will be created and a star will indicate the mean value of the column
    
    if bins:
      sns.histplot(data=data, x=feature, kde=kde, ax=ax_hist2, bins=bins, palette="winter")
    else: 
      sns.histplot(data=data, x=feature, kde=kde, ax=ax_hist2)  # For histogram
    
    ax_hist2.axvline(data[feature].mean(), color="green", linestyle="--")  # Add mean to the histogram
    
    ax_hist2.axvline(data[feature].median(), color="black", linestyle="-")  # Add median to the histogram

# function to create labeled countplots

def labeled_countplot(data, feature, hue=None, perc=False, n=None):
    """
    Barplot with percentage at the top

    data: dataframe
    feature: dataframe column
    perc: whether to display percentages instead of count (default is False)
    n: displays the top n category levels (default is None, i.e., display all levels)
    """

    total = len(data[feature])  # length of the column
    count = data[feature].nunique()
    if n is None:
        plt.figure(figsize=(count + 1, 5))
    else:
        plt.figure(figsize=(n + 1, 5))

    plt.xticks(rotation=90, fontsize=15)
    if hue==None:
      ax = sns.countplot(
        data=data,
        x=feature,
        palette="Paired",
        order=data[feature].value_counts().index[:n].sort_values(),
      )
    else: 
      ax = sns.countplot(
        data=data,
        x=feature,
        hue=hue,
        palette="Paired",
        order=data[feature].value_counts().index[:n].sort_values(),
      )

    for p in ax.patches:
        if perc == True:
            label = "{:.1f}%".format(
                100 * p.get_height() / total
            )  # percentage of each class of the category
        else:
            label = p.get_height()  # count of each level of the category

        x = p.get_x() + p.get_width() / 2  # width of the plot
        y = p.get_height()  # height of the plot

        ax.annotate(
            label,
            (x, y),
            ha="center",
            va="center",
            size=12,
            xytext=(0, 5),
            textcoords="offset points",
        )  # annotate the percentage

    plt.show()  # show the plot

# function to plot stacked bar chart

def stacked_barplot(data, predictor, target):
    """
    Print the category counts and plot a stacked bar chart

    data: dataframe
    predictor: independent variable
    target: target variable
    """
    count = data[predictor].nunique()
    sorter = data[target].value_counts().index[-1]
    tab1 = pd.crosstab(data[predictor], data[target], margins=True).sort_values(
        by=sorter, ascending=False
    )
    print(tab1)
    print("-" * 120)
    tab = pd.crosstab(data[predictor], data[target], normalize="index").sort_values(
        by=sorter, ascending=False
    )
    tab.plot(kind="bar", stacked=True, figsize=(count + 5, 6))
    plt.legend(
        loc="lower left", frameon=False,
    )
    plt.legend(loc="upper left", bbox_to_anchor=(1, 1))
    plt.show()

Customer Profiling by packages -

Basic - Most of the customers here are lower in age(median:32) and monthly income(avg:20K). Majority of them are single or married with Executives working as salaried employee and living in Citytier 1.

Deluxe - Most of the customers are bit higher in age(median:36) and monthly income(avg:22K) compare to basic package customers. Mostly they are managers and work as salaried or having small business. Most of them are married and make 3-4 trips a year. Many divorced or unmarried also prefer this package.

Standard - Most of the customers are around age of 36 and having monthly income is around 26K. They work as Senion Manager and married. They are also salaried and having small business.

Super Deluxe - Most of the customers bit older, around age of 49 and having monthly income is also higher around 32K. They are almost equal in male/female ratio. They work as AVP, salaried and married..

King - These customers are the oldest(median:49) and having highest monthly income(35K) among all others. They are married, have small business and live in city tier 1. Their designation is VP.

Summary of Observations of EDA¶

Age - customers are divided across different age groups. Most of them between 18 and 61. There are no outliers and Age doesn't really affect the customer taking Prod Taken.

Monthly Income - it's rightly skewed and higher income people take more tour packages than lower income people.

City Tier - Customers from lower tier cities take more tour packages compare to tier 1 city customers.

Occupation - All Free Lancer customers tend to take tour packages, however the population for such is very low. Customers with large businesses took more tour packages.

Number of Person Visiting - when customer travel with 2,3 or 4 people, take more tour package compare to when they travel alone or with 5 people.

Number of followups - it shows difference in time sales person does the follow ups. More follow ups tend to increase more customers to buy tour packages.

Passport - passport holder customers tend to buy more tour packages, may be tours are more attracted for international travelling.

Designation - More percentage of Executives buy tour packages compare to any other designations.

Pitch Satisfaction Score - higher the satisfaction, higher the chances of customers buying tour packages.

Marital Status - singles and unmarried prefer more tour packages compare to married.

Product Pitched - customers prefer basic pitch, that attracts them to buy more tour packages.

Number of Trips - customers who do 2 trips in a year tend to buy more tour package compare to customers doing less or more than 2.

NumberOfPersonVisiting is positively correlated with NumberOfChildernVisiting. That means, customers who travel with their children(family) tend to buy more tour packages.

None of the columns having bad data that has to be treated. There are some outliers in few columns and it would be checked later to see if its valid or not.

Creating function to treat outliers. As we know there are many customers after right whisker that look ok. So I am going to multiply IQR (inter quantile range) with 2.75 to create upper whisker. For lower whisker, will keep IQR at standard of 1.5.

In [83]:
def treat_outliers(df, col, low_iqr=1.5, upp_iqr=1.5):
    """
    treats outliers in a variable
    col: str, name of the numerical variable
    df: dataframe
    col: name of the column
    """
    Q1 = df[col].quantile(0.25)  # 25th quantile
    Q3 = df[col].quantile(0.75)  # 75th quantile
    IQR = Q3 - Q1                # Inter Quantile Range (75th perentile - 25th percentile)
    lower_whisker = Q1 - low_iqr * IQR
    upper_whisker = Q3 + upp_iqr * IQR

    # all the values smaller than lower_whisker will be assigned the value of lower_whisker
    # all the values greater than upper_whisker will be assigned the value of upper_whisker
    # the assignment will be done by using the clip function of NumPy
    df[col] = np.clip(df[col], lower_whisker, upper_whisker)

    return df

5. Model building - Comman Pre Tasks¶

In this section, we will perform tasks that would be used by both Bagging and Boosing modeling.

Model evaluation criterion

Model can make wrong predictions in 2 cases -

1) when model predicts that the customer would buy newly created Wellness Tourism Package but customer would not buy when offered.

2) when model thinks customer would not buy the newly created Wellness Tourism Package and it doesn't offer the package but the person would have have bought.

More important case -

In my opinion case # 2 is more important as tourism company would loose potential customers who could have bought the Wellness Tourism Package if offered. That's a bigger loss for a toursim compmany compare to case # 1 where company would just get the rejection from a person.

Measure to consider -

As we want to minimize the loss as per case # 2 above, we should reduce false negatives. That's why the goal should be to maximize the 'recall' score (minimize the false negatives)

Common Functions

Let's create 2 functions which can be used by different models -

1) The confusion_matrix_sklearn function will be used to plot confusion matrix.

2) The model_performance_classification_sklearn will use to calcuate metric scores of the model - Accuracy, Recall, F1 and Precision.

In [101]:
# function to create confusion matrix
def confusion_matrix_sklearn(model, predictors, target):
    """
    To plot the confusion_matrix with percentages

    model: classifier
    predictors: independent variables
    target: dependent variable
    """
    y_pred = model.predict(predictors)
    cm = confusion_matrix(target, y_pred)
    labels = np.asarray(
        [
            ["{0:0.0f}".format(item) + "\n{0:.2%}".format(item / cm.flatten().sum())]
            for item in cm.flatten()
        ]
    ).reshape(2, 2)

    plt.figure(figsize=(6, 4))
    sns.heatmap(cm, annot=labels, fmt="")
    plt.ylabel("True label")
    plt.xlabel("Predicted label")
In [102]:
# defining a function to compute different metrics to check performance of a classification model built using sklearn
def model_performance_classification_sklearn(model, predictors, target):
    """
    Function to compute different metrics to check classification model performance

    model: classifier
    predictors: independent variables
    target: dependent variable
    """

    # predicting using the independent variables
    pred = model.predict(predictors)

    acc = accuracy_score(target, pred)  # to compute Accuracy
    recall = recall_score(target, pred)  # to compute Recall
    precision = precision_score(target, pred)  # to compute Precision
    f1 = f1_score(target, pred)  # to compute F1-score

    # creating a dataframe of metrics
    df_perf = pd.DataFrame(
        {
            "Accuracy": acc,
            "Recall": recall,
            "Precision": precision,
            "F1": f1,
        },
        index=[0],
    )

    return df_perf

10. Summary of Insights & Recommendations¶

As part of this project, we have analyzed the customer data of "Visit with us", a tourism company, to find a way to increase their customer base via offering them the new tour package.

Based on the nature of the objective and the data provided, recall metrics was the best to measure for both the kind of modeling.

To achieve the goal, we tried multiple bagging and boosing modeling techniques. We started with 3 different bagging models (decision tree, random forest and bagging classifier). First we tried with default parameters and then tried with hyperparameter tuning. Out of all these models, we got best results when decision tree was tried with hyperparameters. The recall score was ~ 0.76

Next we tried 4 boosting models. Adaboost, Gradient, XGboost and stack. Again, first we tried as-is with default parameters and then with hyperparameter tuning. The best results we got when we tried stack with tuned estimators like gradient, xgboost, decision tree and randomforest. The recall score was ~0.91. We concluded that was the best model to work with for this dataset.

While working on all these models and doing EDA, I have gatherd below insights and recommendations.

  • Having a passport turned out to be a very important feature in many models. Comapny should encourage their customers to get passport, their likelyhood of buying a package increases. Company can even keep passport application form in the office, provide passport agent contacts to their customers, any such thing that can make customer get passport easily.

  • The number of follow ups has a direct impact in customer buying a tour package. More follow ups result in more sold tour packages. So sales person should not give up on potential clients and do regular follow ups.

  • Cusotmers with higher monthly income tend to buy more tour packages. Also, higher income customers buy Super Deluxe and King packages. By name, it looks like they are expensive ones. Company should try to target higher income customers more so they can sell such high end packages to make more profits.

  • Same like monthly income, customers with older age tend to buy Super Deluxe and King packages. So company should target old customers to get more profit as they would buy such premium packages. Also, the new package that company wants to start revolve around healthier lifestyle, so it would encourage older people more compare to rest.

  • Sales people have 5 different kind pitches for 5 packages. Most of the pitches were either for Basic or Deluxe. Maximum turn around observed in Basic pitch. However, in spite of spending so many pitches (second highest) on Deluxe, the turn around is very low percentage wise. Sales people need to focus more on basic and at the same time either improve upon Deluxe or try save time by cutting down and focus on other packages like Standard.

  • Higher pitch satisfaction score helps to get more customers buy tour packages. Most of the score is around 3, sales people should get trained more so they can improve their score to 4 or 5.

  • It was seen that customers travelling solo or with 5 people do not prefer to take tour packages. Mostly people travelling 2,3 or 4 buy packages. Also, maximum customers who bought packages are single or unmarried. So company should try to lure married people or people with 1 or 2 children to increase their customer base. They can introduce family friendly packages, like resorts with children parks, on-site day care etc.

  • Customers living lower tiers like 2 or 3 prefer more tour packages. Company should advertise more in such tire cities.

  • Customer who prefer 5 start properties tend to buy more tour packages. Company should add more such hotels into their packages and also try to focus on such customers who prefers that.

  • Customer's designation also have important role. During modeling, it was in top features as well. Executives and Senior managers buy more tour packages. Marketing team should invite such people in 'company invited' events. We saw when it was contacted by company, chances of customer taking tour package slightly increases as well.

  • Customer who are Free lancer or have large business tend to buy more tour packages. However, the data is too little for these 2 occupations. Company should try to find more such customers and see if the sales of tour packages increases.
